\begin_layout Standard
The first instruction is LEA.
 It loads address 
\begin_inset Formula $x3F+x3011=x3050$
\end_inset

 (The incremented PC value)+to R3
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The second instruction is LDR.
 It loads the value stored (x70A4) at the address specified in base register
 R3 (x3050) to register R4 using an offset of x0.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The last instruction is also LDR.
 It now loads the value stored at x70A4 to R6, so that it now contains x123B.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

As we load values to three register, and there are no such instruction in
 our set, we assume that we need an instruction that loads the value directly
 to R6.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

For this, we can use the LDI instruction that loads the address of a memory,
 from memory.
 So the instruction would be: LDI R6, x3050.
\end_layout

